WEBVTT

00:01.506 --> 00:04.791
You are listening to a message from First Baptist Church, Wichita Falls.

00:05.292 --> 00:14.327
For more information about First Baptist, click the link in the show notes or go to FBCWN.org.

00:14.347 --> 00:17.512
Today's message comes from Senior Pastor, Dr. Bob McCartney.

00:19.415 --> 00:23.061
Let's open our Bibles this morning to John Chapter 11.

00:23.842 --> 00:28.850
John Chapter 11, I'll begin reading in just a few minutes at verse 17.

00:30.242 --> 00:39.050
I'm beginning a new series of messages rooted in a line from perhaps the most famous poem on all the world.

00:40.152 --> 00:46.197
Perhaps Psalm 23 is the most famous piece of poetry ever written.

00:46.217 --> 00:59.410
And there is that line in verse four, even though I walk through the valley of the shadow of death, I will fear no evil for you are with me.

01:00.386 --> 01:09.560
For the next few weeks, we're going to take a journey and that journey is going to take us to places that we would prefer not to go.

01:09.600 --> 01:13.525
We are going to go into the valley.

01:14.807 --> 01:21.217
And there are a lot of different types of valleys that we have to journey through in the course of our life.

01:22.339 --> 01:24.722
We're going to talk about some of those valleys.

01:25.058 --> 01:27.581
we're going to talk about some low points in life.

01:27.681 --> 01:34.108
And we want to answer the question, where is God when life is at its lowest moment?

01:34.969 --> 01:37.732
Those are questions that are big and they're real.

01:38.953 --> 01:47.443
And so we're going to focus on some of those, but the context of Psalm 23 verse four is the valley of the shadow of death.

01:48.584 --> 01:54.130
And so today we're going to talk about facing death with faith.

01:55.010 --> 02:04.021
In September of 2022, the world was shocked with the news that Queen Elizabeth II had died.

02:05.123 --> 02:07.125
Now, we weren't shocked at her age.

02:07.386 --> 02:09.308
She was 96 years old.

02:10.269 --> 02:19.361
We weren't shocked because she had been on the throne of the British Empire for 70 years, but it was interesting to hear the reactions of people.

02:20.122 --> 02:23.346
Most of her subjects, most of the people in Great Britain,

02:23.586 --> 02:26.230
had never known another monarch.

02:26.791 --> 02:38.128
I mean, you had to, had to be probably past 75 or 76 years old to even have any vague memory of the former king, Queen Elizabeth's father, and that transition of power.

02:38.829 --> 02:42.154
Most people had seen her as the only queen they had ever known.

02:42.955 --> 02:48.504
Because of that, their reactions varied from sadness to stunned.

02:49.746 --> 02:52.530
One lady who was interviewed said, you can't

02:52.962 --> 02:56.886
actually imagine her not being there.

02:58.167 --> 03:05.214
Former British Prime Minister Boris Johnson said, I just always thought she'd be there.

03:06.515 --> 03:22.290
Now this is a 96 year old woman and we understand that death happens and yet when it does come there is a sense of sadness, of denial, of confusion,

03:22.946 --> 03:24.508
and sometimes anger.

03:25.729 --> 03:30.214
So we want to talk about the valley of the shadow of death.

03:31.956 --> 03:33.938
And there's a reason for that.

03:34.879 --> 03:39.464
First of all, all of us are going to lose someone.

03:40.926 --> 03:48.434
If you live long enough, you're going to experience the pain of loss and grief.

03:49.602 --> 03:56.011
And so we want to know how as a follower of Jesus, how do I navigate that?

03:57.313 --> 04:04.224
How do I deal with the loss of grandparents and parents of a spouse?

04:04.244 --> 04:07.448
How would I navigate the loss of a child?

04:09.211 --> 04:12.255
And all of us are going to experience loss and grief.

04:13.297 --> 04:19.506
But the second reality is that all of us are going to face death personally.

04:20.290 --> 04:30.042
Unless the Lord Jesus returns, and that's our hope and prayer, all of us are going to face death someday.

04:31.163 --> 04:36.249
And so we want to know how do we do that with faith.

04:37.331 --> 04:40.915
In John chapter 11, we have this incredible moment.

04:41.856 --> 04:49.906
Jesus receives word that someone who is a very, very close friend is sick.

04:50.658 --> 04:53.782
And I don't mean he has a bad cold and doesn't feel well.

04:54.042 --> 04:56.305
I mean, he is sick unto death.

04:56.345 --> 04:57.927
He is at death's door.

04:58.007 --> 04:59.068
His name is Lazarus.

05:00.029 --> 05:06.497
This is not the same Lazarus who is in the story of Lazarus and the rich man, different Lazarus.

05:07.638 --> 05:08.800
It was a very common name.

05:10.141 --> 05:12.765
But Jesus was very close to this family.

05:13.886 --> 05:20.594
The little village that they lived in Bethany is less than two miles from Jerusalem.

05:21.442 --> 05:37.679
And so it seems that when Jesus would travel to Jerusalem in the late afternoon and early evening, he would retreat and walk to Bethany, and he would stay in the home of Mary and Martha, the sisters, and Lazarus, their brother.

05:38.801 --> 05:41.383
These are people that he had laughed with.

05:41.464 --> 05:44.847
These are people he had ate meals with.

05:44.907 --> 05:48.972
These are people who had helped him with a place to stay.

05:49.032 --> 05:51.154
And so what we expect is

05:51.266 --> 06:07.607
that when Jesus gets word that Lazarus, your friend, the one whom you love dearly is deathly ill. We expect Jesus to drop everything and rush to Lazarus side.

06:08.808 --> 06:10.070
And that is not what happens.

06:11.752 --> 06:16.719
Jesus looks at his disciples and he says, the end of this is not death.

06:16.819 --> 06:17.419
Don't worry about it.

06:18.200 --> 06:19.442
We'll get there when we get there.

06:20.898 --> 06:22.920
And finally they decide to go.

06:23.300 --> 06:32.610
But by the time they get there, Lazarus has been dead and laid in a tomb for four days.

06:33.951 --> 06:38.115
And so we pick up this story in verse 17.

06:39.016 --> 06:42.220
And let's read the first portion of this story.

06:42.260 --> 06:45.323
And then I'm going to work my way through it because the text is fairly lengthy.

06:45.343 --> 06:46.304
Look at verse 17.

06:47.065 --> 06:48.466
So when Jesus came,

06:48.898 --> 06:51.943
He found that he had already been in the tomb four days.

06:52.804 --> 07:00.877
Now, Bethany was near Jerusalem, about 15, stayed away, and many of the Jews had come to Martha and Mary to console them about their brother.

07:01.939 --> 07:08.369
So then Martha, when she heard that Jesus was coming, went to meet him, but Mary stayed in the house.

07:09.290 --> 07:16.722
Martha then said to Jesus, Lord, if you had been here, my brother would not have died.

07:17.218 --> 07:20.022
And even now, I know whatever you ask of God, he will give you.

07:20.944 --> 07:24.950
Jesus said to her, your brother will rise from the dead.

07:26.112 --> 07:33.784
Martha said to him, I know he will rise in the resurrection on the last day.

07:34.765 --> 07:40.654
Jesus said to her, I am the resurrection and the life.

07:41.516 --> 07:45.522
The one who believes in me will live even if he dies.

07:45.858 --> 07:50.363
And everyone who lives and believes in me will never die.

07:50.403 --> 07:54.948
Do you believe this?"

07:56.830 --> 08:07.582
And she said to him, yes, Lord, I have come to believe that you are the Christ, the Son of God, and He who comes into the world.

08:08.483 --> 08:14.930
The first principle that I want us to draw from this incredible biblical story

08:15.522 --> 08:23.574
In order to face death with faith is this, hold on to your faith amid loss.

08:24.616 --> 08:39.058
When you are in the middle of a swirling circumstance that causes your head to spend because someone you love has died, you need to struggle to hang on to your faith.

08:39.906 --> 08:43.272
Now Martha and Mary have very different personalities.

08:43.312 --> 08:46.679
There are a couple of stories in the New Testament that reveal that to us.

08:47.561 --> 08:51.047
Martha is always the one who is a little louder.

08:51.087 --> 08:53.432
Mary is a little quieter.

08:53.472 --> 08:58.802
Martha is a doer and Mary is a feeler.

08:59.458 --> 09:04.084
And so when you see that and experience that in this story, you'll understand a little bit about why.

09:04.504 --> 09:11.173
When Martha hears that Jesus has arrived at Bethany, she jumps up and goes out to meet him.

09:12.234 --> 09:16.439
But Mary remains in the house mourning quietly.

09:17.180 --> 09:19.102
And so she comes out to meet him.

09:20.124 --> 09:23.728
And what we see in Martha's statement is interesting.

09:24.549 --> 09:28.434
There is a bit of confrontation in that statement.

09:29.090 --> 09:32.595
Lord, if you had been here, my brother would not have died.

09:34.097 --> 09:42.208
There's a little bit of disappointment in that statement when she says, Lord, you could have done something and you didn't.

09:43.930 --> 09:48.677
All of us are going to face deaths where we could say those words.

09:49.798 --> 09:54.945
Lord, if you would have been here, someone wouldn't have died.

09:54.985 --> 09:58.610
This circumstance would be different.

09:59.714 --> 10:02.097
Lord, if you'd shown up.

10:02.117 --> 10:08.845
But while there is a bit of confrontation in that statement, there's also a confirmation in that statement.

10:08.865 --> 10:10.127
First of all, she calls him Lord.

10:12.310 --> 10:22.583
And so there's something about the authority that she believes he has, but there's also a faith that she has that says you could have made this different.

10:23.364 --> 10:27.869
You have the power to make this different.

10:27.889 --> 10:28.530
You see there?

10:29.154 --> 10:36.625
While there's a little anger and there's a little disappointment, there is also still a moment of faith.

10:36.685 --> 10:42.153
There is something in Martha's heart that says, Lord, you have the power.

10:42.393 --> 10:47.200
Jesus, you can make this different.

10:47.220 --> 10:54.110
And she says this, even now, even now, I know that whatever you ask of God, he'll give you.

10:54.731 --> 10:56.594
Now that's a significant statement

10:56.706 --> 11:00.231
if you understand what Jewish people believed.

11:01.152 --> 11:10.505
Now I want you to understand that what I'm about to share with you is not biblically true, but it was a widely held belief among Jewish people.

11:11.386 --> 11:22.761
They believed and many of the rabbis taught when someone died that their spirit hovered near the body for three days.

11:24.643 --> 11:26.546
And after the third day,

11:26.818 --> 11:27.999
All hope was lost.

11:28.079 --> 11:31.202
That spirit had to depart to the realm of the dead.

11:32.263 --> 11:33.084
And there was no hope.

11:34.285 --> 11:40.311
Well, it is significant that Jesus waits until the fourth day.

11:41.292 --> 11:43.675
This is really important in the story.

11:44.275 --> 11:46.137
It's not just chronology.

11:46.177 --> 11:47.999
It's not just the passage of time.

11:48.459 --> 11:52.483
Jesus is going to crush a false belief.

11:54.585 --> 11:55.186
And so,

11:56.322 --> 12:01.949
She says to him, even now, even after four days, I know whatever you ask of God, he'll give you.

12:02.850 --> 12:06.515
And I know that my brother and Jesus says, your brother will rise again.

12:07.135 --> 12:13.403
She says, I know in the resurrection on the last day that I'll see him again.

12:13.523 --> 12:16.487
She has faith that someday she'll see him again.

12:18.469 --> 12:25.618
And then Jesus makes really what is the climactic statement of the passage, but there's a lot more to the story we'll get to.

12:26.242 --> 12:31.109
when he says, Martha, I am the resurrection.

12:32.712 --> 12:35.776
I am the life.

12:35.796 --> 12:40.223
Jesus is saying the resurrection isn't just an event.

12:41.044 --> 12:47.134
The resurrection is wrapped up in a person and Jesus says, I am that person.

12:48.636 --> 12:51.440
You see, resurrection doesn't just happen.

12:53.002 --> 12:55.346
You can meet people every day

12:56.194 --> 12:58.557
who believe they're gonna see their loved ones again.

12:59.298 --> 13:02.382
Because they believe there's a heaven and they believe they're going.

13:02.402 --> 13:05.566
But if you ask them specifically, what is that rooted in?

13:05.626 --> 13:08.149
They cannot tell you it's rooted in Jesus.

13:09.351 --> 13:17.061
The resurrection hope is only found in a relationship with Jesus Christ.

13:17.582 --> 13:19.324
It's not just an event.

13:19.624 --> 13:21.386
The resurrection is a person.

13:23.409 --> 13:24.210
Jesus says,

13:25.314 --> 13:26.235
And you know what Martha?

13:27.117 --> 13:32.405
Everyone who believes in me will live even if they die.

13:32.465 --> 13:39.876
And everyone who lives and believes in me will never die.

13:40.057 --> 13:41.619
Now those aren't contradictory statements.

13:42.701 --> 13:54.098
What Jesus is saying is there's a part of you, this part right here, this part that you can feel and touch and see and hug and kiss on the cheek

13:55.906 --> 13:57.949
That part is going to die.

14:00.652 --> 14:02.354
But it can live again by resurrection.

14:03.936 --> 14:05.218
But there is a part of you.

14:05.758 --> 14:10.464
There is a part of every one of you that will never die.

14:11.566 --> 14:13.648
And that's the part, that's the unseen part of you.

14:14.389 --> 14:15.571
That's your spirit and soul.

14:15.651 --> 14:20.237
And that part of you that dies can live again by resurrection.

14:20.477 --> 14:24.402
But there is a part of you once it is made alive in Christ that will never die.

14:25.154 --> 14:33.002
That's what Jesus is saying because that part of you will depart from the body when it dies and go to be in the presence of the Lord.

14:33.762 --> 14:40.729
And then Jesus asked her a question and I'm going to tell you it's the singular, most important question that's ever been asked.

14:40.749 --> 14:45.594
In my opinion, from the Bible, it is the bottom line question of all of life.

14:46.155 --> 14:49.518
Do you believe this?

14:50.579 --> 14:53.682
And your answer to that question makes all the difference.

14:55.010 --> 14:57.654
Do you believe this?

14:58.696 --> 15:08.612
You see, what Jesus is calling on Martha to do is Martha, in the midst of this loss, in the midst of this pain, hold on to your faith.

15:10.756 --> 15:11.356
Don't let it go.

15:13.159 --> 15:22.194
Pain, grief, loss has a way of putting

15:22.434 --> 15:26.220
a puncture in our faith, like a pinhole in a balloon.

15:28.644 --> 15:29.686
And it can leak away.

15:31.969 --> 15:33.532
Levi Lusco is a pastor.

15:35.094 --> 15:43.328
In 2012, his five-year-old daughter, Lina, had an asthma attack.

15:43.348 --> 15:44.309
She stopped breathing.

15:44.790 --> 15:46.112
They started CPR.

15:47.174 --> 15:49.778
And five-year-old Lina died in his arms.

15:52.194 --> 15:53.075
There is nothing.

15:53.316 --> 15:54.317
There is nothing.

15:54.838 --> 16:06.553
I've been a pastor for a long time and I'm going to tell you, the loss of a child is the absolute worst thing I have ever tried to help people navigate.

16:07.374 --> 16:10.038
There is nothing like it, nothing.

16:13.282 --> 16:17.027
And Levi and his wife worked through that.

16:17.989 --> 16:21.874
You know, the stats are not good for couples when they lose a child.

16:22.786 --> 16:24.449
The divorce right, skyrockets.

16:25.731 --> 16:28.516
But they decided, we're not going to let go.

16:29.959 --> 16:31.301
And they clung to one another.

16:32.062 --> 16:33.184
And they're still married today.

16:35.208 --> 16:37.692
He said, I stood at her grave side.

16:39.636 --> 16:47.730
And I said these words, Christ, you are resurrection and you are life.

16:50.018 --> 16:57.768
He said, I had to repeat those words to myself over and over as I buried my five year old daughter.

17:00.251 --> 17:08.802
And from that moment, his faith, though it was wounded and hurting, was buoyed.

17:08.842 --> 17:15.570
It was lifted because he came to learn that

17:16.034 --> 17:18.677
The resurrection isn't just for someday.

17:18.697 --> 17:21.361
Resurrection power is for every day.

17:23.223 --> 17:25.947
And it is to help you through the losses of life.

17:27.549 --> 17:35.338
You see, standing at a grave site and saying that is not some cheap religious platitude, that is faith, that is forged in a fire.

17:35.599 --> 17:36.400
That's what that is.

17:39.183 --> 17:41.366
Hold on to your faith in the midst of loss.

17:41.787 --> 17:44.530
And that's what Martha does, by the way.

17:46.082 --> 17:54.174
Martha says to him, yes, Lord, I have come to believe that you are the Christ, the Son of God, he who comes into the world.

17:55.075 --> 17:57.638
So Martha hangs on to her faith in the midst of loss.

17:58.600 --> 18:03.687
Second, allow Jesus to meet you in your grief.

18:04.548 --> 18:06.491
Allow Jesus to meet you in your grief.

18:06.551 --> 18:07.793
Now look at verse 28.

18:08.935 --> 18:14.162
When she had said this, she left and she called Mary, her sister, saying secretly,

18:14.434 --> 18:16.536
The teacher is here and he's calling for you.

18:17.657 --> 18:21.601
And when she heard this, she got up quickly and came to him.

18:23.143 --> 18:27.467
Now Jesus had not yet come into the village, but was still at the place where Martha met him.

18:28.428 --> 18:37.577
Then the Jews who were with her in the house and were consoling her, when they saw that Mary had gotten up quickly and left, they followed her thinking that she was going to the tomb to weep there.

18:38.898 --> 18:42.642
So then Mary came to the place where Jesus was and

18:42.946 --> 18:50.454
She saw him and fell at his feet saying to him, Lord, if you had been here, my brother would not have died.

18:51.975 --> 19:03.106
Therefore, when Jesus saw her weeping and the Jews who came with her also weeping, he was deeply moved in spirit and was troubled.

19:04.308 --> 19:05.809
And he said, where have you laid him?

19:05.849 --> 19:10.674
And they said to him, Lord, come and see Jesus' weapon.

19:12.226 --> 19:15.791
So the Jews were saying, see how he loved him.

19:15.891 --> 19:24.062
But some of them said, could this man who opened the eyes of a man who was blind not have also kept this man from dying?

19:26.025 --> 19:33.054
The second principle is allow Jesus to meet you in your grief.

19:33.074 --> 19:38.642
Jesus enters into the grief of Mary and Martha.

19:39.618 --> 19:50.090
And when Mary hears that Jesus is there, she goes to meet Him and she says to Him, Lord, if you had been here, my brother would not have died.

19:50.110 --> 19:52.953
Now I'm going to tell you something.

19:54.475 --> 20:04.246
If two people come to you separately with the same complaint and say the same thing, they've been talking.

20:06.969 --> 20:08.210
I'll guarantee you that.

20:09.218 --> 20:14.867
And by the way, the crowd of mourners, they say exactly the same thing.

20:15.929 --> 20:20.937
Could not this man who opened blind eyes have also saved this man from dying?

20:21.958 --> 20:23.200
They've all been talking about it.

20:24.322 --> 20:29.089
And yet Jesus comes to meet them in their grief.

20:30.632 --> 20:37.042
The word for weeping that is used when it refers to Martha and to Mary,

20:37.634 --> 20:43.160
and to that crowd of mourners is a word that we would better translate wailing.

20:44.841 --> 20:53.750
Morning in the ancient world of the Middle East was always done with loud cries.

20:54.511 --> 20:56.213
They let their grief out.

20:57.494 --> 21:01.178
You know, we civilized 21st century middle-class Americans.

21:01.758 --> 21:05.362
We kind of hold it in, but they let it out.

21:05.858 --> 21:08.542
and they grieve out loud.

21:10.665 --> 21:14.732
And Jesus comes and he enters into their grief.

21:15.973 --> 21:21.842
In verse 35, that shortest of verses in the Bible, Jesus wept.

21:22.463 --> 21:25.328
He came to grieve with them.

21:25.869 --> 21:30.516
That's interesting that there are two words that are used for weeping in this passage.

21:30.536 --> 21:32.018
The word that is used

21:32.290 --> 21:36.396
for Martha and Mary and the crowd is that word for loud wailing.

21:36.436 --> 21:44.587
The word that is used of Jesus when it says Jesus' whip is actually only used one time in the entire New Testament.

21:45.208 --> 21:50.496
It's the only place it's used and it means a quiet cry.

21:51.096 --> 21:55.222
It's that picture of someone who's choked up, who's on the verge of tears.

21:55.883 --> 21:57.906
And the Bible tells us that Jesus

21:58.274 --> 22:02.299
was deeply moved in his spirit and he was troubled.

22:02.560 --> 22:06.165
He enters into the pain of these mourners.

22:07.446 --> 22:17.560
This is a picture, not of weakness, but of divine compassion that Jesus comes alongside us when we grieve.

22:18.641 --> 22:28.274
Psalm 34 verse 18 says, the Lord is near to the brokenhearted and he saves those who are crushed in spirit.

22:29.410 --> 22:45.891
in September of 2022, Hurricane Ian swept onto the southwest coast of Florida, and there were storm surges that wiped out entire towns, that wiped out entire neighborhoods of homes.

22:46.612 --> 22:57.426
And as the people began to clean that up, and they began to realize they had lost everything materially that they had ever collected, there were these

22:58.018 --> 23:02.944
Christian relief agencies that came in, you helped sponsor some of those through your offerings.

23:02.984 --> 23:19.685
We send part of our offering to send relief and to the North American Mission Board and to the International Mission Board to help relieve the pain of those moments and those big send relief trucks and Texans on mission trucks roll in to those places to feed people and to help them.

23:21.047 --> 23:26.514
There was an interview with one man who had lost everything and he says,

23:26.690 --> 23:30.394
The best thing that happened to me is he stood in the debris of his home.

23:30.955 --> 23:35.360
He said, the best thing that happened to me was not somebody who came and helped me clean this stuff up.

23:36.521 --> 23:45.050
But someone with a yellow hat on came and they knelt down beside me and they prayed for me and they cried with me.

23:47.333 --> 23:52.979
Sometimes it's not solutions that people are looking for.

23:54.140 --> 23:55.602
It's compassion.

23:56.546 --> 23:57.607
that they're looking for.

23:58.328 --> 23:59.270
It's what they need.

24:00.511 --> 24:04.397
And so allow Jesus to meet you in your grave.

24:04.457 --> 24:11.847
You can do more than grieve after you grieve, but first you must give voice to your grief.

24:12.888 --> 24:17.935
Third and finally, resurrection hope overpowers the grave.

24:17.955 --> 24:22.962
Look at verse 38, resurrection hope overpowers the grave.

24:23.362 --> 24:27.608
So Jesus again, being deeply moved within came to the tomb.

24:28.249 --> 24:30.472
That was a cave and a stone was lying against it.

24:31.373 --> 24:33.256
And Jesus said, remove the stone.

24:34.298 --> 24:41.728
Martha, the sister of the deceased said to him, Lord, by this time there will be a stench for he has been dead for four days.

24:42.850 --> 24:45.714
Jesus said to her, did I not say to you?

24:46.114 --> 24:49.217
that if you believe, you will see the glory of God.

24:49.297 --> 24:58.387
So they removed the stone and Jesus raised his eyes and said, Father, I thank you that you have heard me, but I knew that you always hear me.

24:58.447 --> 25:04.073
Nevertheless, because of the people standing around, I said it so that they may believe that you sent me.

25:04.554 --> 25:12.242
And when he heard and when he said these things, he cried out with a loud voice, Lazarus, come out.

25:12.706 --> 25:19.254
And out came the man who had died, bound, hand and foot with wrappings, and his face was wrapped around with cloth.

25:19.274 --> 25:22.638
And Jesus said, unbind him and let him go.

25:22.698 --> 25:25.822
Victory over death.

25:25.862 --> 25:30.788
You see, resurrection hope overpowers the grave.

25:32.090 --> 25:32.550
Pardon me.

25:33.692 --> 25:38.958
Jesus, the Bible says, is deeply moved and he takes action.

25:39.599 --> 25:42.002
He says, remove the stone, roll it away.

25:42.946 --> 25:51.639
Now, Jesus could have just with the twitch of his finger and his almighty power could I guess could have just rolled that stone away, but he asked for help to do that.

25:52.521 --> 25:53.082
It's interesting.

25:53.803 --> 26:01.815
He says, I want you to roll the stone away, but Martha object, she says, or there will be a terrible smell if we roll this stone away.

26:02.837 --> 26:11.570
I mean, look, the Egyptians, embalmed, they mummified bodies.

26:11.682 --> 26:14.706
the Israelites and the Jewish people didn't do that.

26:14.726 --> 26:26.440
They simply took a body and laid it in the tomb and in the heat of the arid climate of Israel, bodies began to decompose really quick.

26:26.460 --> 26:28.743
And there would be an awful, awful smell.

26:29.484 --> 26:32.468
And Jesus says, no, I want you to roll that stone away.

26:32.488 --> 26:38.035
I know you think this is hopeless, but then Jesus prays a prayer.

26:38.956 --> 26:40.818
And Jesus prays that prayer

26:41.346 --> 26:47.134
so that there could be no doubt about it that God had answered that prayer and God performed the miracle.

26:48.215 --> 27:03.376
And so Jesus calls for Lazarus to come out of that tomb and Lazarus comes out wrapped around with the cloths that would have been wrapped around a dead body and he comes walking out of that tomb.

27:05.319 --> 27:10.546
You see what Jesus does in that moment is he proves

27:11.138 --> 27:15.464
that he will be victorious over the final enemy.

27:15.704 --> 27:18.308
That's what 1 Corinthians 1526 calls death.

27:19.069 --> 27:22.013
The last enemy to be destroyed is death.

27:23.555 --> 27:25.638
And someday death is going to be destroyed.

27:26.660 --> 27:35.512
This past week, we saw the incredible story of hostages being released from that Hamas terrorist group in Palestine.

27:36.754 --> 27:40.018
One of those was a man named

27:40.130 --> 27:42.654
Etaar David.

27:43.816 --> 27:54.393
And Etaar David was taken hostage from the Nova Music Festival on November 7th, 2023, when those Palestinian terrorists cut through that fence and came across.

27:54.433 --> 27:58.699
He was one of the first people taken and he had been in captivity all that time.

27:58.739 --> 28:06.552
But one of the things that those terrorists did to him was they videotaped him and they gave him a script.

28:06.572 --> 28:07.954
They told him what he had to say.

28:08.738 --> 28:11.522
And they videotaped him digging his own grave.

28:12.423 --> 28:13.905
They made him dig his own grave.

28:14.726 --> 28:18.851
And he was telling the people, you have to negotiate, you have to withdraw.

28:18.911 --> 28:21.815
He's reading this Hamas script that they had given him.

28:22.276 --> 28:24.439
And he's literally digging his own grave.

28:24.459 --> 28:27.022
He's saying, they're going to kill me if you don't surrender.

28:29.105 --> 28:36.274
And when David came back and he walked out, it was as if a man came back from the dead.

28:38.178 --> 28:43.784
He looked like a skeleton that was animated with skin on it.

28:44.765 --> 28:49.230
He was so frail and so weak that he could hardly stand on his own.

28:51.112 --> 28:54.355
Folks, there's a greater miracle than that in this passage.

28:55.296 --> 29:01.663
And it is the miracle that Jesus called forth a man who had been dead for four days.

29:02.164 --> 29:03.365
He hadn't dug his own grave.

29:03.385 --> 29:04.847
He'd been in one for four days.

29:05.888 --> 29:07.890
And Jesus demonstrates

29:08.578 --> 29:14.224
through this resurrection sign miracle that a greater resurrection is coming.

29:15.425 --> 29:20.330
A greater resurrection is coming in that he will give his own life.

29:21.291 --> 29:22.632
He will surrender his life.

29:22.912 --> 29:25.855
Nobody killed him, nobody executed him, nobody assassinated him.

29:26.156 --> 29:32.862
Jesus gave his life and he laid it down so that he could take it back up again.

29:34.764 --> 29:36.626
In Acts chapter two, verse 24,

29:37.698 --> 29:50.134
Peter says, but God raised him up again, putting an end to the agony of death since it was impossible for him to be held by its power.

29:51.595 --> 29:55.460
You see, the power that death has over us is sin.

29:57.062 --> 30:06.514
But when a sinless sacrifice dies, death has no authority to hold him, so he

30:06.594 --> 30:07.896
defeats death.

30:09.058 --> 30:14.086
Jesus went to the tomb to beat death to death.

30:18.493 --> 30:21.238
And he comes forth on that first Easter.

30:23.521 --> 30:33.778
Our hope is not rooted in the vain, perhaps silly belief, maybe.

30:34.946 --> 30:37.450
that God would cause grandma to come back from the dead.

30:39.192 --> 30:52.071
You know, I wonder if Lazarus, who was righteous man, who had gone to a place of peace and comfort, thought, why did you bring me back to this sin-soaked world?

30:53.833 --> 30:55.295
I mean, have you ever thought about it this way?

30:55.355 --> 30:56.897
Lazarus had to die twice.

30:58.580 --> 31:00.082
Eventually he would die again.

31:04.130 --> 31:17.405
And yet Jesus offers us a very real hope, a resurrection hope that overcomes death.

31:17.465 --> 31:20.308
This is how you face death with faith.

31:23.131 --> 31:33.202
You come to the understanding that someday resurrection means reunion.

31:35.170 --> 31:40.136
That's how Levi Lusco coped with the death of his five-year-old daughter.

31:42.960 --> 31:53.494
That's how those of us who have experienced the searing loss of sudden death, or even an anticipated death.

31:55.396 --> 31:57.619
This is how you hang on to hope.

31:59.321 --> 32:03.186
Resurrection means reunions.

32:04.994 --> 32:06.498
for those who've trusted Christ.

32:09.425 --> 32:12.712
You've been listening to a message from First Baptist Church, which is not false.

32:13.274 --> 32:22.275
For more information about First Baptist, including gathering times and locations, click the link in the show notes or go to FBCWF.org.

32:22.295 --> 32:23.538
We'll see you next week.

